  "notes": "Navajo (Din√© bizaad), Southern Athabaskan (Na-Dene), written in a Latin alphabet standardised in the 1930s (Young & Morgan). Stops and affricates come in three laryngeal series: plain/unaspirated (b d g dz dl j), aspirated (t k ts t≈В ch) and ejective (t Љ k Љ ts Љ t≈В Љ ch Љ); note that orthographic вЯ®b d gвЯ© are voiceless unaspirated [p t k], not voiced. вЯ® ЉвЯ© standing alone is the glottal stop / Ф/. Four vowel qualities a e i o, each in four shapes: short oral, long oral (doubled letter), short nasal (ogonek: ƒЕ ƒЩ ƒѓ «Ђ) and long nasal (doubled ogonek letter). TONE CONVENTION: Navajo is a two-tone language; HIGH tone is written with an acute accent (√° √© √≠ √≥, nasal ƒЕћБ ƒЩћБ ƒѓћБ «ЂћБ) and LOW tone is unmarked (the default). This spec therefore emits the IPA acute (U+0301) on high-tone vowels and nothing on low-tone vowels; nasalisation is U+0303 and length is ЋР. Long vowels with mixed tone (rising вЯ®a√°вЯ©, falling вЯ®√°aвЯ©) fall out of the sequence of the two short-vowel graphemes and are not listed separately. No tone_inventory is declared because the acute/unmarked convention is orthographic rather than an IPA tone-letter inventory.",
